Introduction

As you all are working through your mini-projects I figured it would be useful to revisit/review some approaches for what I affectionately call “chopping tables”. This is a brief/high level overview of some dplyr commands, but mainly it is to think about how we attack working with and manipulating tabular data. In short, if we have an idea of what the shape of our table should look like, then we can have an idea of what our approach should be, whether it’s in R, Excel or ArcPro.

Ideally, you can use this document alongside the slides we went over earlier on tables as a way to guide you. As such, I won’t spend too much time going over certain things I discuss in the slides. Check those resources and the resources in the syllabus for even more detail.

We’ll be making use of the Licenses and Inspections codes violations from OpenDataPhilly This dataset is useful because it’s a relatively modest sized dataset and has a nice combination of categorical and continuous variables. We should have 434,792 observations across 32 variables (how can we tell?).

Choppin’ Tables

Okay…let’s start. A basic question we want to always ask ourselves when we’re working with our tables is what is our unit of analysis? In other words, what is the unit we actually care about in terms of summaries and how is that unit represented in the table? What is the unit of analysis for our violations table? One way to think of the your unit of analysis is what configuration of your variables that makes each row distinct (e.g. no duplications?). Depending on the type of data you have this may be single column (such as a true primary key in a database) or it may be a combination of columns (such as a table with FirstName, LastName, Birthday as a potential ID across multiple columns). For this table the unit of analysis of our table should be the casenumber. But is that the case? Let’s take a quick look.

Checking for duplicates

There are many ways to check for duplicates. The approach I’m offering here uses dplyr, but there are base-r, Excel or any number of approaches here. What’s important is you understand why this matters and the logic I’m taking.

violations_dupes <- violations %>% 
  group_by(casenumber) %>% 
  tally() %>% 
  arrange(desc(n)) %>% 
  head()

If you view your violations_dupes dataframe you should see 6 ticket numbers and a column “n” which is the count of the number of times those ticket numbers appear in the dataframe. Let’s break down our call here.

  1. I feed violations into a group_by(casenumber) because we want to know whether our tickets are duplicated, and then pipe into a tally() which will give us a count of each instance of that ticket number found in our dataframe.
  2. Because we want to be sure we can see cases that are actual duplicates without looking 400k+ rows we will arrange our output by n (the number of times a ticket number is found in the dataframe) in a descending fashion
  3. Finally, we take the top-6 results using the head() function.

Note the 3 basic steps here, calculate the number of instances of our tickets, arrange those counts in descending order and then give me the top 6 results. What you should see if this table has duplicates! In fact, each casenumber can be repeated multiple times. You can confirm this by exploring your dataframe in RStudio. Click on it in your local environment, sort the casenumber column and look at the values.

So, after closer inspection it seems like the true unique ID is the violationnumber column. So, let’s check for dupes there, what do you see? I’ll let you reproduce the duplication step again on your own. I will say to return to all columns this time and check one of the duplicate rows.

Check the code underneath here for one way of doing this. But experiment with an approach first.

Code 
viol_check2 <- violations %>% 
  group_by(violationnumber) %>% 
  tally() %>% 
  filter( n > 1)


dupe_rows <- as_vector(viol_check2$violationnumber)

viol_check3 <- violations %>% 
  filter(violationnumber %in% c(dupe_rows))

Let’s break it down:

  1. We now have our pretty standard group_by() and tally() lines, but this time we add an additional filter() call to keep only our duplicate rows
  2. our viol_check2 dataframe now has two columns: one for violation number and one for the count of the rows for each violation number
  3. But we want to pick out those rows from our larger dataframe so we can see what’s going on…how do we solve this?
    1. We create a new vector called dupe_rows and we use the as_vector() function from the purrr package (another tidyverse package) on the violation number column from our viol_check2 dataframe
    2. Take a look at your local environment so you can what dupe_rows is
  4. Finally, we create a new dataframe, viol_check3, where we filter() our original violations table but we keep only the dupe_rows violations from the violationnumber column using the %in% operator we’ve discussed before

What is it about these rows that make them duplicates? It’s unclear! There are a few sources of duplication here. Let’s investigate a bit…we will pull out a specific address:

De-duping the table

Okay, let’s drop these dupes. In this case, we have a pretty clear duplication that has a pretty straightforward solution. Let’s a take a look.

violations <- violations %>% 
  distinct(violationnumber, .keep_all = TRUE)

This should look relatively straightforward. We use the distinct() function from dplyr, we tell it which column we want distinct rows for, and because we want to keep all of our other information we make the .keep_all = function equal to TRUE. If we did not tell the function we wanted to keep all of our columns it would return only the distinct ticket numbers. If you’re curious if it worked, then take a look at our example address from above and see what comes up now in our dataframe.

Frequency of Violations

Okay. We should have a de-duped table, now we can do some work. Let’s start with the frequency of different kinds of violations.

violation_ct <- violations %>% 
  count(violationcodetitle) %>% 
  arrange(desc(n)) %>% 
  slice_head(n = 10)

Let’s break this down. I introduce a couple of new functions here, but if you run the command you should see what we’re doing.

  1. Take our violations() dataframe and pipe it into our count() function. count() is another convenience function in dplyr that combines group_by() and tally() in one. In other word this is equivalent to explicitly grouping on the violation description and then piping that into tally.
  2. We take our counts and arrange them in descending order by their frequency
  3. We get the top 10 results by using the slice_head() function from dplyr

The results should look something like this for you.

Calculating Some Summary Values

Next, we will calculate some summary values. Because these are primarily categorical variables I will demonstrate a couple of ways to look at frequencies and calculate proportions. Then, finally, we’ll do some summary values by geography by bringing in some census data.

Violation Status Proportions

Okay, let’s start relatively small. What proportion of violations are closed, open etc? How can we attack this?

  1. Get a count of the number of the rows by the case status
  2. Divide the the number of rows by the total number of observations to get a proportion
case_prop <- violations %>% 
  count(casestatus) %>% 
  mutate(case_prop = n/sum(n))

So, we did something a little different here. We used our count() function and then piped that into a mutate(), but note our case_prop expression. We take the quotient of n, or the count of rows, over the sum(n) or the total number of instances of n! This is a handy way of getting proportions when we’re dealing with frequency tables.

Case Status Proportions
casestatus n case_prop

Violation Proportion by Case Status

This is a pretty flexible approach and we can use it for multiple groups. Let’s say we want to see what proportion of cases are still in violation by violation type. Here’s one way we can approach it (let me know if you figure out some different/better ways).

  1. Get a count of violations by their violation code and case status
  2. Get the sum of violations by the violation code
  3. Calculate the proportion of violations by their case status for their violation code
  4. Grab those rows that are still in violation and have greater than equal to 3,000 violations (to cut down on the large number of rows)
open_viols <- violations %>% 
  count(violationcodetitle, casestatus) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  group_by(violationcodetitle) %>% 
  mutate(viol_code_total = sum(n),
         viol_code_prop = n/viol_code_total) %>% 
  filter(casestatus == "IN VIOLATION", viol_code_total >= 3000)

We make a LOT of steps here so run these lines in smaller chunks if you’re having trouble reading them. But our basic steps were as we outlined above. Note that I added ungroup() here. We technically don’t need to add an ungroup() as the count() function is generally smart enough to not carry our grouping structure, but sometimes we just want to be extra careful and so we tell dplyr that remove any groups that may be on our dataframe, then we re-group our dataframe on our violationcodetitle column and use mutate() to add our new columns of interest. Finally, we throw in our filter() commands. These final steps should seem more familiar by now.

This is an example of why we have to be clear about what our unit of analysis is. We can explore multiple dimensions from a single table based on how combine certain variables and subset our rows. This is the essence of chopping tables.

Some Quick Summaries by Geographies

Okay, we have mastered our table by itself, but what if we need to know different rates or proportions by some geography like census tracts? Well…this is where spatial joins can come in! But how to join them? We’ve done some variant on this before, but let’s sketch it out:

  1. Get census tract boundary files from tigris
  2. Convert our violations dataframe to a simple features dataframe using st_as_sf()
  3. Join our violations to the tracts and calculate some summaries

So, again, we want to be clear with ourselves as to what our unit of analysis is. Because we’re mapping tracts our unit of analysis must be the census tract, so everything will have to eventually correspond to those boundaries. But, before we do all that let’s get our boundary files and join our violations data.

philly_tracts <- tracts(state = "PA", county = "Philadelphia", progress = FALSE) %>% 
  select(GEOID)

violations_sf <- violations %>% 
  filter(!is.na(lng)|!is.na(lat)) %>% 
  st_as_sf(coords = c("lng", "lat"), crs = 4326) %>% 
  st_transform(crs = st_crs(philly_tracts))

viol_tracts <- philly_tracts %>% 
  st_join(violations_sf) %>% 
  as_tibble() %>% 
  select(-geometry)

Okay, what should we see in our viol_tracts dataframe? We had to make sure we had no NAs in our long/lat columns so we have our filter() call to return those rows where both the lng and lat columns have values. We then converted our long/lats to points and converted to our geographic coordinate system, WGS84, and then projected our points to the projection of the tracts. Ideally, this rhythm should feel familiar to us.

Next we join philly_tracts to violations_sf using st_join(). The default topological relationship for st_join() is an intersection which works just fine for us here. So, now we should have each violation associated with a tract and our geometry column should be a tract. Finally, I convert this simple features dataframe back to a regular dataframe and drop the geometry column.

Now, why would I do this? Again, think about the unit of analysis we ultimately want versus what unit we are currently working with. Our joined dataframe has many duplicate GEOID rows. Why? Because we have multiple violations per tract and for mapping we, ideally, only have one tract in our final table.

Now R is fully capable of doing these summaries with simple features dataframes, but it spends a lot of processing power working with your geometries. This eats up processing time. A faster approach to to convert our dataframe to a non-spatial dataframe, summarise up, and then join back to our boundary file as needed! This also gives a way to build up a dataset over time if we so choose.

Violation Status by Tract

Let’s reproduce some of our earlier summaries, but now by tract. Now, in order to simplify and to save our computers our basic workflow will consist of this:

  1. Convert our simple features dataframe back to a regular dataframe
  2. Calculate our values of interest
  3. Reshape our table to make sure we have only one row per tract
  4. Join our non-spatial dataframe back to our original simple features boundary and map
case_prop_tract <- viol_tracts %>% 
  group_by(GEOID, casestatus) %>% 
  tally() %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  group_by(GEOID) %>% 
  mutate(total_viols = sum(n), 
         viol_prop = n/sum(n))

Okay…these steps should look familiar. We calculate the number of violations by their case status by the census tract. Then we ungroup, just to be careful, re-group on our GEOID and then add two new columns, the first is the sum of the violations by tract and then we calculate the proportion of violations by case status by tract.

This is basically what we did above, but now we have an extra grouping variable because we need to have it organized by tract.

Next, if we want to map this data in ArcPro or some other desktop GIS we need to reshape our dataframe. Why? Because we still have duplicate tract IDs, and, ultimately, we want to join back to our original boundary file for easy mapping. In order to do that we need each row to represent one tract. But right now we have a long table where our casestatus column holds multiple values per tract. We will make our table wider, then, by using the pivot_Wider() function from tidyr (another great tidyverse) package.

case_prop_wide <- case_prop_tract %>% 
  pivot_wider(id_cols = GEOID, names_from = casestatus, values_from = viol_prop)

case_prop_wide <- case_prop_wide %>% 
  janitor::clean_names("snake")

Let’s break this down. pivot_wider() requires an id_cols = argument. This argument tells the function what is the unique identifier for your row. In this case, it’s GEOID. We then tell it what should be the names of our new columns and we will pull this from our casestatus column and, then, finally, because we are only really interested in our violation proportions we tell pivot_wider() to only pull out the values for our viol_prop column. We could bring back more values if we want, but this starts to blow up the number of our columns. It really depends on what you’re ultimately looking to do. For the sake of simplicity we are only returning this. Finally, we feed our dataframe into the clean_names() function from the janitor package just to make sure our column names have no spaces or special characters in them (remember to install the janitor package if you have not done so, you can throw it into your p_load() call at the beginning of your script). Note, I specify “snake case” here. The final dataframe should have 408 observations, each one corresponding to a tract. Now, let’s join back and map.

Mapping Our Summary Values

Okay…so now we need to join our summary dataframe to our tracts simple features dataframe and then we can map our summary values.

philly_tracts <- philly_tracts %>% 
  inner_join(case_prop_wide, by = c("GEOID" = "geoid"))

The join should look pretty familiar here. We use inner_join() because were joining a spatial to non-spatial dataframe and I’m specifying the join column just to be careful, and for reproducibility.

Let’s look at the proportion of in violation cases by census tract for Philadelphia.

tm_shape(philly_tracts) +
